Communication - Annotations

  1. Use geom_text() with infinite positions to place text at the four corners of the plot.
last_plot <- ggplot(mpg, aes(hwy, cty)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(
    label = "Top left",
    x = -Inf,
    y = Inf,
    hjust = 0,
    vjust = 1
  ) +
  geom_text(
    label = "Top right",
    x = Inf,
    y = Inf,
    hjust = 1,
    vjust = 1
  ) +
  geom_text(
    label = "Bottom right",
    x = Inf,
    y = -Inf,
    hjust = 1,
    vjust = 0
  ) +
  geom_text(
    label = "Bottom left",
    x = -Inf,
    y = -Inf,
    hjust = 0,
    vjust = 0
  )
  1. Use annotate() to add a point geom in the middle of your last plot without having to create a tibble. Customize the shape, size, or color of the point.
# Look above for the last plot used. I'm going to extract the range values of the plot. You can check the code piecemeal to see how I'm extracting the values:
x_max <- layer_scales(last_plot)$x$range$range[2]
x_min <- layer_scales(last_plot)$x$range$range[1]
y_max <- layer_scales(last_plot)$y$range$range[2]
y_min <- layer_scales(last_plot)$y$range$range[1]

last_plot +
  annotate(
    geom = "point",
    x = (x_max + x_min) / 2, y = (y_max + y_min) / 2,
    color = "red", shape = 15, size = 5
  )

  1. How do labels with geom_text() interact with faceting? How can you add a label to a single facet? How can you put a different label in each facet? (Hint: Think about the dataset that is being passed to geom_text().)
label_info <- mpg |>
  group_by(drv) |>
  arrange(desc(displ)) |>
  slice_head(n = 1) |>
  mutate(
    drive_type = case_when(
      drv == "f" ~ "front-wheel drive",
      drv == "r" ~ "rear-wheel drive",
      drv == "4" ~ "4-wheel drive"
    )
  ) |>
  select(displ, hwy, drv, drive_type)

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~drv) +
  geom_text(
    data = label_info, 
    aes(x = displ, y = hwy, label = drive_type),
    fontface = "bold", size = 5, hjust = "right", vjust = "bottom"
  ) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

  1. What are the four arguments to arrow()? How do they work? Create a series of plots that demonstrate the most important options.

They are angle, length, ends and type

angle controls the angle between the diagonal lines of the arrow and its base line length controls the length of the diagonal lines of the arrow in inches ends describes where to position the arrow head. Options of "last", "first", or "both" type describes if the arrow head should or shouldnt be a closed triangle. Options of "open" or "closed"

data <- data.frame(
  x = c(0, 50, 5, 5),
  y = c(0, 50, 5, 5)
)

ggplot(data, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point() +
  annotate(
    geom = "segment",
    x = 3, y = 35, xend = 25, yend = 25, color = "red",
    arrow = arrow(angle = 90)
  )

ggplot(data, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point() +
  annotate(
    geom = "segment",
    x = 3, y = 35, xend = 25, yend = 25, color = "red",
    arrow = arrow(length = unit(1, "inches"))
  )

ggplot(data, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point() +
  annotate(
    geom = "segment",
    x = 3, y = 35, xend = 25, yend = 25, color = "red",
    arrow = arrow(ends = "first")
  )

ggplot(data, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point() +
  annotate(
    geom = "segment",
    x = 3, y = 35, xend = 25, yend = 25, color = "red",
    arrow = arrow(type = "open")
  )

  1. Placing breaks every 4 years (this is trickier than it seems!).
four_years <- seq.Date(from = presidential$start[1], to = tail(presidential$start, 1), by = 365 * 4)
# There is a better way of doing the above using lubridate package in `graphics-for-communication.Rmd` under the first edition solutions to this book

new_presidential |>
  ggplot(aes(x = start, y = name_id, color = party)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = end, yend = name_id)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(Republican = "#E81B23", Democratic = "#00AEF3")) +
  scale_x_date(name = NULL, breaks = presidential$start, date_labels = "'%y",
               minor_breaks = four_years) +
  scale_y_discrete(NULL) +

new_presidential <- presidential |>
  mutate(
    id = 33 + row_number(),
    name_id = fct_inorder(str_c(name, " (", id, ")"))
    )

new_presidential |>
  ggplot(aes(x = start, y = name_id, color = party)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = end, yend = name_id)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(Republican = "#E81B23", Democratic = "#00AEF3")) +
  scale_x_date(name = NULL, breaks = presidential$start, date_labels = "'%y") +
  scale_y_discrete(NULL) +
  annotate(
    geom = "segment",
    x = presidential$start[11], y = (45 - 33), xend = presidential$start[12], yend = (45 - 33), 
    colour = "purple",
    arrow = arrow(type = "open", angle = 20,)
  ) + # Remember that the y-axis actually goes from 1 to 12, so the y-axis tick labels may be misleading
  annotate(
    geom = "text",
    x = new_presidential$start[10], y = (45 - 33), label = "Current President", 
    size = 3, colour = "purple"
  ) +
  theme_bw()

  scale_color_manual(values = c(Republican = "#E81B23", Democratic = "#00AEF3")) +
  scale_x_date(name = NULL, breaks = presidential$start, date_labels = "'%y") +
  scale_y_discrete(NULL) +
  annotate(
    geom = "segment",
    x = presidential$start[11], y = (45 - 33), xend = presidential$start[12], yend = (45 - 33), 
    colour = "purple",
    arrow = arrow(type = "open", angle = 20,)
  ) + # Remember that the y-axis actually goes from 1 to 12, so the y-axis tick labels may be misleading
  annotate(
    geom = "text",
    x = new_presidential$start[10], y = (45 - 33), label = "Current President", 
    size = 3, colour = "purple"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(colour = "blue", face = "bold"))
